The Higgs boson analyzes
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs-Boson has aroused a certain amount of excitement last summer, and this for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
Finally, it is the last particle, whose existence of the standard model - our best or least false explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - was predicted, but empirically not yet observed.
But for the physicists it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented at a major physics conference in Kyoto this week, but data is still missing to be completely secure.
However, let us assume that this is actually the Higgs, because apparently there is only a small risk of cheating, and let us look at what it is all about.
In this world, there is an inevitably indispensable law, which means that two objects cannot be present at the same time in the same place.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try too hard because you will get hurt.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law applies to them as well: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantity state", whereby this "state" consists largely of some of their characteristics.
From this the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner there are the good citizens, who are called Fermiones and are kind of obeying the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons are moving, a bad band of anarchists who are not holy - at least not this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups, according to the website The Particle Adventure, by the Berkeley laboratories (which, by the way, is absolutely amazing): the mesons that we will not treat here and the "particles of power", through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
But it has to be stressed here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "bote" of electromagnetic force.
If a particle with an electric charge accelerates or the direction changes, the electromagnetic field is exactly in this place "disturbed", like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbation" produces an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "threshers of the force".
Stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, has to be "disturbed" so that this boson shows up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must achieve very high energies, a little similar to a frozen pond, whose surface could only be feared by a very large rock.
That is why a huge particle accelerator like the CERN is needed - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a size of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
There are indeed not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold itself on the refrigerator.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those doing so possess a mass, while the others (as by the way, the photon) do not possess a mass.
For what can all these researches be "good", does Mrs Plamondon ask?
For science, they are used to verify the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to examine exactly all the differences between the observations and the forecasts of the SM.
There are, by the way, numerous physicists who are eagerly hoping that such deviations will be found, as the least difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes of the model.
One has to say that the latter still has great shortcomings, because it does not explain the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (renews ups!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found at CERN.
Impact
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there would be no such thing.
By the way: in the early 1960s, laser pioneers in the Bell labs did not assume that their works would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but otherwise nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first long-range laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 himself - has already said that the laser was considered at the beginning rather than a "laboratory playing".
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also arise from all the instruments surrounding the research.
For example, during his work in optics, in 1969, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor.
Although it wasn't the original purpose, this sensor now serves as an eye for all digital cameras worldwide and has won him the Nobel Prize for Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you can really never know it...
Palliative care - the best way to die...
Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life with its Committee on Death in Dignity.
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer, which ate him, had given him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I made seven years," he said, half-hearted, lying in his bed in the home for Palliative Care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its work: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he wishes to be helped while eating.
Couragefully, he even manages to smile and speak to strangers who are busy around him, bring him his drugs, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to heal my diarrhea, as it is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"During our life, we learn that a man pees standing," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
Returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for certain persons.
"This depends on the ability of the person", to take a step backwards, he notes.
In the view of several people working in the Palliative Care, major events take place in the midst of these setbacks.
The patients who are sent to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, the doctors and nurses who care for them will no longer be overcrowded with so-called "healing" care.
For Ms. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
But through the illness I really got to know my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more wishes in life," she says, before accepting that a mask is put on to help her breathe.
She still expects a final visit to her son from Italy in the next few days.
At the Victor-Gadbois home you can offer with a group of volunteers body care and help with the food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other possibilities.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec, there is a bed for the palliative care of 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little if you take into account that one day we're all going to die.
Life will continue here under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is granted oral care with Brandy or Pepsi, as desired.
Diabetic patients no longer have to check their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drown the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We are helping families and patients alike," says care director Nathalie Savard.
At home Victor-Gadbois is not a day like the other.
Aside from an old 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family meeting in the court and is well supported by his pillows, while being held in his honor, a 36-year-old young man, surrounded by his parents, his wife and two little children, dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"Since six months, three to five beds have always been filled with cancer patients under the age of 45," Dr. Christiane Martel says worriedly.
53% of the patients admitted to the home of Victor-Gadbois come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care that is intended to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter has reached the final stage of their lives, either at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as Victor-Gadbois's home and the company for residential palliative care in the Greater Montreal area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great insufficiency in the health care of Quebec that makes sure that a number of doctors specialised in palliative care are confronted with concerns about the adoption of a law on the regulation of death aid and assisted suicide.
Since the month of October, a manifesto has been in circulation signed by prominent figures of the Palliative Care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health care system is not powerful enough to ensure that all rights to high-quality palliative care are guaranteed before they are accepted as a means of dying.
Shortly ago, she says, I saw a patient who had 14 days of great pain in the emergency room without taking measures to alleviate it.
I fear that patients will only die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients in spite of the worst forecasts obliterated until the last day.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she discontinued a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she told me that she was sorry that I would give up the fight, she told me.
But she told me I was in the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nurse for not allowing this desire after their pain has been alleviated by a team of Palliative Care.
However, it must be clearly stated that the palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, Head of Palliative Care of the Society of Domestic Palliative Care of Greater Montreal, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors thus often resort to the terminal sedation, which leads to either sporadic or permanent inclusion of the patient until the time of his death.
We can no longer act as if we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly be able to access this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not alleviated all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to put me in," but "I want my pain to be alleviated."
