A Constitution with the Brechstang in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever with regard to the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To the surprise of all, he announced on Wednesday that the Constitutional Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had granted this plenary session two additional months to complete his work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been relying on a text which has been provisionally amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to a legal confusion.
This new initiative has only brought about an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "stepping justice with his feet".
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, which forces the brothers to renounce their intention to explain to the Egyptians the text section for section.
For the President, it is also a way to regain its public and democratic legitimacy while the protests are raging throughout the country.
After confirmations in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Mohammed Mursi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will be happy to vote.
In particular, an ultimatum is put to the Egyptian people with this recourse to an accelerated vote: "Neither does it agree with my draft or I keep the unlimited authority", the latter was supposed to end after the Constitution was adopted.
85 Most of the Islamist members of this constitutional assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of Liberals have not complied with the call.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned away because they felt that they had not been able to put their views into effect.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to reach a decision, 11 people, deputy members, were added yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some are very close to the Moslems.
It is not surprising that the articles were generally adopted unanimously.
The commentators found it interesting, by the way, that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed for prayer at the time, since some members of the committee felt that the pendant watch of the congregating assembly did not go exactly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which all drew attention to itself, remains the same as that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important requirement, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made it possible for a stricter application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is proof of their good will and respect for the other members of the Egyptian society.
"Holyness" is the answer to the liberals who regard this only as a propaganda strike.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
In doing so, they have in particular the eye of Article 220, which confers an advisory role on the University of Al-Azhar, in particular with regard to the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt's specialist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because "the people invited to deliver an opinion have not been elected and do not possess any democratic legitimacy.
