In Israel Ukrainian tourists await sacred places, the navel of the world and a sea of Sole
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of Bible truths, modern comfort and an unspoilt nature.
AIF will name you the five main reasons for visiting Israel.
Bend Before Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It means that all who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the conversion of water into wine at a wedding celebration, walking on water, the silence of the sea tower and fishing.
Here Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
However, most of the sanctuaries are found in Jerusalem.
The path of suffering or the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa) is carried out by believers here.
The path begins at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretoria, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the grave church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the salving stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, in the Christian view, is the umbilical navel of the world symbolizing the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands in the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree grew, from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place of the Jews - the walls of complaint, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in the year 70 A.D..
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave there paper with wishes that then go into fulfillment.
Take a trip uphill
The ruins of the Massada fortress form the remains of the secret hiding from enemies that Herod of the Great built for his family in the year 25 AD.
They are located on a rock wall in the mountains at a height of 450 meters above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins of their own strength.
All the others bring a cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at altitude from 1600 to 2040 meters is the famous ski resort Hermon, in which it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can reach it with a shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometres.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods were allegedly living on the mountaintop.
Visit unique museums
In this country there are almost 300 museums.
Not all of them can be visited on one trip.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
One of these is the Israel Museum, not far from the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or scrolls of the Dead Sea found in rock caves in the Judean desert are kept, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There the collection of works by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited.
In Akko you can visit the museum in the Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the then visitors and bath servants.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are neither museum guides nor souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most striking section is the monument for the children built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the space there is complete darkness.
Star funnel.
And the names of the children of the Jews and of the lands in which they died shall be heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing something for your health
The three main recreational areas of Israel lie on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
There are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums in each of the three places.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is bathed in the winter months as the water temperature does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there is bathed throughout the year.
By the way, with a position of 417 meters below sea level, this unusual sea is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and thus even carries non-swimmingers easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt soles) and healing mud as well as for the treatment of inflammation of the skin, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and the calming of stressed nerves.
Touch the secrets of antiquity
These secrets contain the old town of Tel Aviv, the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city, the famous seaway, which linked Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia, ran together.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved here the beautiful Andromeda, with which he led a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after stars.
According to legend, Fortuna is to be held by all who touch the walls in the alley with their starsign.
In Jaffa, you can find newly married couples from all over Israel and even from other countries at photo dates.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can strip through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In the Roman era Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
In the carefully restored theatre evening concerts and operas are performed today.
Favourites for tourists
If you're going to Israel, don't worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money on the trip is not taken with you in euros, but in dollars that can simply be exchanged in shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city, you usually get ahead by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a high-speed train and in Haifa the country's only subway line with six stations connecting the lower town with the upper town.
In fact, it is an underground cable car.
A ride within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the mode of transport, which is enough for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
And on Sunday morning the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, excluding pork, seafood, fish without sheds and food containing both milk and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between various dishes of ham and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pure beans and peas (flakes) as well as fruits and vegetables.
In the streets of Israel’s cities there are no strangling dogs.
For this, there are many well-kept cats who strut comfortably and unheavyly through the streets.
In the evening they are even seen sleeping on the roofs of parking cars.
The cats like places to be lively and don't say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a car rental costs between 37 dollars a day (Hyundai Getz) and 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance also costs 15 dollars a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
The average cost of admission tickets for museums is 30 shekels.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of the adventurers and holiday seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Country, which represents an increase of 51% compared with the reference period in 2010, before lifting the visa requirement on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MPs and citizens' lawyers are discussing the benefits of the Law on Compulsory Language Tests for Migrants, criminals are already dealing with counterfeit certificates.
Each year 13 million host workers come to Moscow, St Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are Central Asian citizens: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Its only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of families remaining in the home.
On 1 December, a law entered into force requiring every migrant worker to take a test attesting knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this scheme applies only to migrants who want to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing sector and in the retail trade.
However, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
In doing so, we must not only carry out language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the foundations of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated both for the maintenance and extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is an official language.
Also excluded are persons who received their certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Purpose, problems and protection of rights
The examination units will be run by the Puschkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of Friends of Peoples, Moscow State University, St Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take tests in all cities; already more than 160 centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the MPs of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
On the other hand, before the law came into force in the press several times, civil rights lawyers asked the following question: What does this really mean?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills, both for the Russians and for the host workers?
Above all, the purpose of reducing the number of forced labour is to dissociate the spokesman of the Migration Agency.
"Many people are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," says Viktor Sebelev, Head of Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must be protected before their departure.
Only organized recruitment will solve the problems of foreign workers to 90%.
Problems are encountered by unskilled migrants, education, language skills and medical examinations.
Zebelev is convinced that a future migrants without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who put him under the pretext of help in a dark, narrow barrack, where he will endure with dozens of his like months without food and documents and will create 12 to 14 hours a day.
Many complaints from our migrants reach us.
"In your home country, the one promise will be made, and when you arrive, you will be betrayed, their passports will be taken away and will not receive the promised wage," confirmed Tolib Schwaripov, Head of Labour Migration Administration of the Tajik Migration Agency.
Don't be shy, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian Republics, who want to earn their money in Russia, admit that they are not only able to speak the language of the destination country, but also can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmens, Usbeks and Tajik can achieve reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone buy them decent clothes, shoes and school goods.
As a teenager, these children immediately take the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil society lawyers stress the following important aspects of the law.
The test must only be carried out by legal migrants.
If you do not have this status, there is no exam and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers continue to stay illegally in Russia.
"Holy welcome" or "Forbidden access"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic obstacles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
Legalization also costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are for the most part faked and we are not registered, and cases of blackmail arise from this.
"You want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," the Tajik Umed Huschkadamov says to journalists.
"Don't hide any costs for false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it became apparent that not only the registration documents of migrants can be forged.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by Federal Migration Agency staff.
The faked papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get it for nothing: each migrant who hoped to be able to avoid the tests paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: this costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important direct task is to protect the system from corruption so that certificates cannot be purchased simply means that both officials and civil servants agree.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time that they will have time for a basic language course.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered places in areas where there is no need for active understanding with people.
