On that day, some Walmart employees, of whom there are 2.2 million worldwide, laid down their work and worked together with trade unions and left-wing activists branches of the chain, whose target group is people with low and medium income.
Walmart sells all products, from windmills, hunting guns and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The product in the Walmart branches is on average between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
This is why many of the low-paid Walmart employees buy only at their own workplace.
The prices and product range made Walmart one of the largest companies in the USA.
According to critics, Walmart can often sell the goods only so cheaply because the employees are poorly paid.
The latter also complain about heavy working conditions, for example missing forklifts or hand scanners.
The protesters on Black Friday called for wage increases and expressed their concern that the contribution to the company's own health insurance had increased from $30 to $100 a month.
A typical Walmart employee who earns $9.5 an hour cannot afford this increase, they said.
Researchers from the California University in Berkeley prove that if the company raised the average salary to 12 dollars per hour, it would cost Walmart 3.2 billion dollars.
That's about 1.1% more than they donate for pay now.
If Walmart would fully transfer the wage increases to customers, each purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
This would be for them per year compared to today's additional spending of only 12.39 dollars.
Proponents of Walmart note with satisfaction that there were only protests in nine states and that they did not give the company any losses.
The Black Friday took the next day in its shop from 8 am on Thursday to midnight, and during this period Walmart sold about 5000 items per second.
On "Black Friday", the Walmart cash registers accounted for nearly 100 million transactions.
The company's spokesman, Dan Fogelman, claimed in an interview on the website of the left-wing Huffington Post that "less than five" Walmart employees in total had ceased their work and the protest action had only been "an additional PR trick" of the union that organized the protests.
"Free cash box!"
