In the context of public procurement, the Czech Republic has good control bodies and adequate laws, but it is not able to apply them.
In the discussion for Aktuálně.cz, this is said by the Vice-President of the Supreme Control Office (Nouvy the control of the NK), Miloslav Kala.
"A law is never perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and I do not think this is the case with us," Kala comments on the current situation.
A similar result appears to be common control by Czech and German auditors.
As a negative example of practice, he points out the appointment of Prime Minister Petr Nečas to the so-called "Black System".
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not harass entrepreneurs with controls - is the system therefore banned or allowed?
"A law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then the head of government cannot simply come, and the control office, whose duty is once again the control of compliance with the law, hinders its activities," Kala notes.
At the check-up committee meeting of the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint Czech-German project, which compared the laws of both countries on public contracts.
What was it about?
This is a parallel examination that we started about two years ago.
Simply put, it is about European legislators defining how public contracts can be handled, building on national legislation, and finally, there is the actual practical application.
We have compared all this with each other, and although the test has not yet been completed, we have found very interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws are perhaps even more "harder and perfect", but the actual application in Germany is better in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to establish new and more precise rules over and over again. It is also necessary to consider the actual application of the law.
How can the project help you? What results from this project?
Such joint control could help us to stop constantly striving for the perfection of laws and the reduction and elimination of thresholds if this does not seem to have a particularly positive effect.
Economy means buying a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But the reduction of thresholds for orders does not guarantee that we also achieve this goal.
Perhaps it is even the case that in this way we only burden the system with excessive "paper crane" and those looking for gaps in the system have much easier to exploit than if the thresholds remained higher.
They talk about the problems in the practical implementation of the Czech Procurement Act.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar authority here to our NK, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NKū is the Federal Accounting Court, which is built up just like us and also has a college that is formed only slightly differently. In principle, however, both authorities work similarly.
The competences are also to a certain extent comparable, but Germany is a state, i.e. there are these accounts also in the individual Länder - in which the German system differs from ours.
The BRH is only allowed to control federal funds, which corresponds to our state funds.
Public funds managed by the districts and municipalities are subject to the control of the national accounts.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it easier than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare this without specific information. Nevertheless, Germany is often referred to as an example in some respects, but it is certainly not possible to say that Germany is better in everything.
Is this perhaps because the examiners are better there?
That is certainly not true, but as I have said, I do not like such comparisons very much.
It is worth noting that even those countries that are a model for us also face problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have anything to do with our authority, would they?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, what was the significance for your authority of the amendment of the Procurement Act, do you already feel any impact?
