Šimon Ornest: At our concerts we want to collect positive energy
What do you think about the fact that in less than a month, the world's downfall is supposed to take place?
That's one of those disaster reports that we're so happy to jump into.
With our band The Tap Tap, we're more than laughing at it and saying that we're the only band in the world that can collect enough positive energy to stop or prevent the collapse of the world.
In December, you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you present the project to our readers?
This is a nationwide benefit event that we have been planning for two years.
To this end, we want to use the marketing potential of the Maya calendar, the end of which is forecast for 21 December at 11:10 a.m.
On the day before, i.e. 20 December, three concerts will be held simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava from 21:00 on 20 December.
The end of the concerts is said to be at about the time to which the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific Island of Kiribati, which is in a time zone of 12 hours ahead of us.
Who's this idea come from?
Originally I guess, after which we designed the idea together with our graphic artist Honza Augusta.
In doing so, we do not only want to collect enough positive energy to prevent the collapse of the world, but also, together with the public, we want to think about the state in which we once hand over this world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Maya calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and key chains against the collapse of the world, with which people can also support us through www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap has also recorded, together with other performers, the so-called hymn against the collapse of the world with the title "Worldfall falls out".
Already today the hymn on YouTube is very popular. Will it also be heard at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, provided that everything works and the end of the world does not take place...
The hymn is to be sung at the same time by all performers at all three concerts.
In addition, the hymns are transmitted live together in a direct circuit from the Czech television.
The text of the hymn comes from Tom the Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, and Xindl X sings with...
How did you come to the cooperation with both?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many benefit events and concerts...
We are working hard to involve these people in our projects.
It turns out that most people are interested in working with us and have fun.
What is the purpose of the proceeds of concerts against the collapse of the world?
For the establishment of the accessible education centre Studeo, where we have been working for six years together with the association Tap at the Jedlička Institute.
The students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the resources to visit the editors, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building is to be created, in which we will then enter with this project.
Several groups and performers perform at each concert.
What criteria did you choose?
We wanted to create a program that appeals to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere perform with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Ji the Searchý.
Find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "great events" planned for the future too?
In May we will perform for the first time at the spring in Prague, and also for this concert we prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are already in the USA - would like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not just small, so far you have been in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
However, The Tap Tap is a group composed of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It is not as bad as it appears at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair drivers, i.e. the wheelchairs have to be transported in the luggage room. Furthermore, we have to carry many instrument suitcases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems so far, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that sometimes I have already wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travel abroad you have a comparison of how it looks with accessibility in each country, how you deal with disabled people there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, where everything works better than with us, we witnessed in Russia that everything is still in its beginnings in the East.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is absolutely not accessible to people with disabilities. It is still unusual there when someone in the wheelchair is travelling alone in the city centre.
It is not even obvious there that you leave a wheelchair driver in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to point to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what ways do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There's still a lot of things we're after...
However, it should be noted that an improvement in the situation is always dependent on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public space, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
But it is not common for a larger group of disabled people to participate actively in social events there, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect for the public and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come out of our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular. But if we go back a few years: What motivated you to set up a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a supervisor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in getting involved with something intense.
And since I am a musician myself and play among other things saxophones, I have founded a music AG together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our presenter, L the Angelovič, says, something is out of control (laughs).
But the band only became known in the last few years, or am I mistaken?
It is true that the collaboration with well-known singers has helped us, and we have also begun to actively promote for ourselves.
We have become aware that if you do something and this is not visible outwards, your performance in a certain sense does not exist.
Thanks to EU funding, we can also afford good readers, high-quality equipment and other things.
Was it your goal to bring it so far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential that things could be handled differently.
In the show business today, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is viewed with caution and is only accepted after a long time.
There are only a few really unique things, and I dare say that Tap Tap belongs to it.
Of course, the first impression the spectator has most of the time is compassion; that's only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely unnecessary because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live and develop a full life, provided they have the means to do so.
I always say that if people with disabilities succeed something, this is not only progress for themselves, but for the whole of society.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, how to hear from many people?
If you want to do something good, you must not compromise in many things and you must also ask for some discipline.
This is, in my view, quite normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find that they have twice a week sample, have to complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert trips, the enthusiasm disappears at many quickly.
But this is how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many of them have been involved since the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only one: L the Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come and go, you can't stop it.
Whoever has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome with us.
