Poland and space.
Last week, at a ministerial meeting of the member countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth largest member of this space authority. Poland is thus the second member country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started working closely with ESA in 1994 and took part in several ESA projects in the following years.
The path of Poland into space, of course, started much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, not always understanding it.
I recall here, for example, the lecture by A. Šternfeld of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented ideas from his pioneering work "Introduction to Cosmoautik".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (b. 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch in 1934 for "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's worldwide recognized contribution to the development of space has been appreciated for being named after him by one of the craters on the Earth side of the moon.
Already in 1925 a railway drone was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clarified whether the rocket should be used for starting or braking the drains.
The information to this effect comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933 the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered guns.
The research was carried out by the Institute of Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaf Mokryckiegi.
The documents submitted show that the research has been carried out through to the stage of practical tests.
The research was, of course, interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the technical press of the design of a photoelectric hunting dragon by Ing. Rohoziński appeared in the press, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work, its work was terminated from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space were published in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Company (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this company was in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space are devoted.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to set up a space company.
At the time there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was to be expected that the exploration of space would have the future.
As early as 1956, the Polish space company PTA was working to join the International Federation for Space, founded in 1951, and in fact PTA became a regular member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA Chairman, Kazimierz Zarakiewicz (1902 - 1959), was appointed Deputy Chairman of the International Federation of Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first start took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh quite 5 kg.
Later an improved version was built, the RM-1A, and in 1959 started flight tests with the two-stage rocket RM-2 in the Bēdów desert.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to carry out real scientific work - the rocket RM-34 should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high winds.
In 1962, however, further developments were discontinued.
==Meteor-1 rockets==In 1962 to 1965, the meteor-1 rockets were developed as a successor to the first RM rockets.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) have been developed from this rocket, which differ from one another in the size of the transport area for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rockets had a transport space with 0.4 litres capacity, Meteor-1B with 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C with 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight altitude was 37 km for all three types.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor 2 rocket was developed at the aviation institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg at a height of about 60 km.
Then the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, to which two years later the establishment of a national COSPAR committee followed.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second Intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimir Remek.
