The movie Argo: If it's worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist students occupied the US Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostages.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the fallen Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had kept the patronage over his regime for decades.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the American government - it could not afford to throw the Shah on board, as this would have seriously damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a serious blow to the reputation of the united states, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt of hostage liberation only made everything worse.
The diplomats captured were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been arranged by the Algerian government.
The fate of hostages brought out a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the USA a small partial victory.
Right before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy staff managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees from Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to cover their true identity - they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff who allegedly visited film locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert for "Exfiltration", Tony Mendez, also required the collaboration of Hollywood.
In order for the cover to be credible, articles about this film project appeared in specialist journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of multiple film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful housepiece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This changes the mood levels in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no major differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and easily oversawed.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the floor of office, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has succeeded with this film a remarkable restart of his career.
A smiled actor has become a respectable director, and as an actor he is no longer the goal of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the Crime No Children's Game (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the Thriller City without Grace (2010).
At the same time it is Affleck's first film, which does not play in the director's home Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that removed the previous films of this director from the standard Hollywoods.
However, Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran of Canada is "played".
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the entrance sequence of the destruction of the message is very impressive in its perceptuality, yet conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictableness that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team also have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the wrong movie staff on a Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the film sense.
But with the few he works quite successfully, sometimes helping the reality - which then doesn't always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the threatening crisis at Tehran Airport is turned away from a telephone in America, or even the persecution hunt on the runway, seem a bit clever).
The weakness of Argo is its all too wide scattering, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters would have earned more space, and so they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses a bit of pull. It is a film that can be tracked with a certain interest and, at the same time, the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70th century.
However, enthusiasm is only a matter of difficulty.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive to this day, and as proof of it, as has been overtaken by the ideas of the omnipotent and omnipresent secret services, it is sufficient.
