Szabo: "Germans have to play a bigger role"
Germany has abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on US-European relations, Berlin thus balances at a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had initially signaled that it would vote against the request for observer status of Palestinians with the United Nations.
But then it was Berlin.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I do not think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the rebellion in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting when it came to setting up a flight ban zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is precisely turning its foreign policy away from a policy that, to put it mildly, was managed by the US, towards a German foreign policy.
It is difficult to say that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans thus find themselves in between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still working on their role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy such as that of France or the United Kingdom.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to take positions that are independent of those of the US or European partners in the case of national interests.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other major powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position of the Middle East conflict and the vote in the United Nations?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it must be careful not to attack the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
It certainly matters.
But I wouldn't want to give too much weight to that either, that's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining from important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I believe that there is a great deal of understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the USA.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even show some respect for it.
For it does signal that it is taken seriously as an international player and its interests must be considered.
There are different opinions on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The US, on the other hand, clearly voted in favour of a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the government under Obama probably has quite a lot of understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, publicly represent this position.
I do not think that the actual differences of opinion are as great as they always appear.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, then Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policy at all.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand, and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a bit easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is currently not the case.
So they cannot be part of a wider line and must instead push things out of their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe into a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, already because of the relationship with Israel.
That was always a sensitive subject.
But I think the German is clear that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany itself see itself as an important international player - does Germany want to play a leading role at all?
Or does Germany still have a difficult leadership role to play?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
For example, when we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany takes on a larger role, different anti-German feelings become clear.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this way, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It must be acceptable to different neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
Now the influence of the United States in European policy is constantly decreasing, but the EU is not filling up at the moment, who else is staying?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it's unpleasant for them and makes them much more unpopular - c'est la vie!
