The most difficult profession in the world: the human working animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano put their lives and their health at stake when they carry 70 kilos of sulphur across the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others work literally in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 mineworkers who earn their lives by bringing sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano to the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
For this to happen, he must climb down to the ground of his crater every day, where the sulphur-containing gas flowing from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulphur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the abominable paths of stone.
Although it is only 250 metres to the top of the volcano, rising to an altitude of 2386 metres, the exhausted wearers need more than 40 minutes for the climb at the tortoise pace, maintaining balance and carefully setting their steps so that they do not slip and fall.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed on the steep slopes of the Kawah Ijen years ago.
The mine workers of Kawah Ijen earn 5 Eurocents for each kilo of sulphur they degrade.
At the top, they follow the path between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and walk with the tiringly heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has set a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who since 1960 has been using the deposits in the volcano and (don't say better) its workers, who pay 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocents) for each kilo of sulphur.
This is then sold to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocents) each, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"As we usually carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for every way," Anto explains, who normally makes three routes a day.
For each route, it takes three hours, after which it is completely done, but at the end of the day, it then brings together 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros).
But what looks like a miserable wage for such an awfully inhuman effort is threefold of what he would deserve with field work.
"The daily wage of mine workers here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid per day at the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees ( 167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not as hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, for a reason that is as important in Indonesia as the sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to convert her to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughs often and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases.
The 27-year-old Anto has been putting his life on the Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulphur has already left the first traces at him, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughs often and his eyes are irritated due to the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for reaching his dream.
"I will work here for another two years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
This friendly and intelligent young man, who has been punished by life, could work as a tourist guide, waiter or at the reception of a hotel, but instead he does the work of a carrier.
It divides a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and stands up every morning at two o'clock, because the sulphur also flows out at night, where its characteristic yellow color shines in the dark blue.
Challenged by the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlight on his helmet, which he has bought from his own money.
About 400 carriers load the basket with sulphur on their shoulders at the crater floor.
Despite its great profits, the mining company has not mechanized the sulphur reduction to save costs, and does not provide any equipment to the carriers that work on their own account and are paid for by weight.
They also do not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) per camera, which the guards of this nature park together with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) demand from the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human carrier.
