He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will continue "as long as it goes" because he needs the money to raise his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life.
Even if the sulphur burns the throat and the eyes cry, when the wind suddenly turns and the mine workers cling to the thick columns that rise from the crater, the men are so hard that no one complains about serious diseases ... of course except for the usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and bladders on the shoulders that have distorted themselves from the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on its back, Unainik is only able to carry 50 kg at the age of 53.
Every day he and his companions break 15 tons of sulphur from the volcano transported by three trucks through a goat path between the bush to the camp in Tamansari 18 kilometres away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life," explains Unainik, opening his mouth far, missing some teeth.
Of his five children, the elder also works as a sulphur carrier at the age of 30.
Time passes, but poverty continues generation by generation in one of the hardest occupations in the world: those who work as a human burden on the Kawah Ijen.
